    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Health Checks and Auto-Heal for Multi-Service Platforms</title>

    <summary>Health monitoring and automatic recovery for multi-service platforms on Ubuntu 24.04 VPS. Three layers: HTTP /health endpoints (liveness + readiness with dependency checks), systemd watchdog (Type=notify, WatchdogSec=30s, application sends WATCHDOG=1 every 15s), and an auto-heal watcher process (checks all services every 60s, restarts on 2+ consecutive failures, 5-min cooldown, max 3 restarts/hour, sends Telegram alerts).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Solo-operated platforms have no on-call rotation. Without automatic recovery, a crashed Celery worker or hung API process stays down until the developer notices — potentially hours later. Systemd handles transient crashes (Restart=always); the watcher handles hung processes that pass systemd's is-active check but fail actual health probes.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Multi-service platforms where a Celery worker, API, or bot can silently fail</item>
        <item>Services that can hang (respond to systemd but stop processing) — systemd alone won't catch these</item>
        <item>After deploy: confirming all services pass health probes before marking deploy successful</item>
        <item>Implementing /health endpoints in FastAPI/Django services for external monitoring integration</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple single-service deployments where Restart=always in systemd is sufficient</item>
        <item>Managed platforms (Heroku, Railway, Render) that provide built-in health check restarts</item>
        <item>As a replacement for proper structured logging — health checks detect failure, logs explain it</item>
        <item>Setting WatchdogSec below 10s — application must notify at half the interval; too short causes false positives under load</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="liveness-vs-readiness">
      <list>
        <item>Liveness — is the process alive and responding? systemctl is-active or /health/live (returns 200 with no body)</item>
        <item>Readiness — can the service handle requests? /health checks all dependencies: DB, Redis, message queue. Returns 200 if all OK, 503 if degraded.</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always return 503 when any critical dependency is unhealthy, not 200 with an error body.</statement>
        <rationale>Load balancers and health check scripts check HTTP status codes, not body content. A 200 with {"status":"error"} will be treated as healthy.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="systemd-watchdog">
      <p>Type=notify + WatchdogSec=30s: the application must send WATCHDOG=1 to the NOTIFY_SOCKET every 15s (half the interval). If it stops sending, systemd kills and restarts the process — catching hung states that still pass is-active.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Send watchdog notification at WatchdogSec/2 interval, not WatchdogSec. This provides a safety margin before systemd triggers the kill.</statement>
        <rationale>If the notification thread hangs right after sending at exactly WatchdogSec, the next cycle may be too late. Sending at half the interval provides one missed cycle before restart.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="auto-heal-watcher">
      <p>A long-running watcher process polls all services every 60s. On failure: 5-minute cooldown between restart attempts, max 3 restarts per hour per service. Prevents restart storms.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Check methods: HTTP /health, systemctl is-active, Celery inspect ping</item>
        <item>Restart command: systemctl --user restart service-name</item>
        <item>Restart count decays: subtract 1 per successful check cycle</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="fastapi-health-endpoint">
      <example type="good" title="FastAPI health endpoint with parallel checks">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import time, asyncio
from fastapi import FastAPI, Response

app = FastAPI()
START_TIME = time.time()

async def check_database():
    try:
        start = time.time()
        async with db_pool.acquire() as conn:
            await conn.execute("SELECT 1")
        return {"status": "ok", "latency_ms": round((time.time() - start) * 1000, 1)}
    except Exception as e:
        return {"status": "error", "error": str(e)}

async def check_redis():
    try:
        start = time.time()
        await redis_client.ping()
        return {"status": "ok", "latency_ms": round((time.time() - start) * 1000, 1)}
    except Exception as e:
        return {"status": "error", "error": str(e)}

@app.get("/health")
async def health(response: Response):
    checks = {}
    checks["database"], checks["redis"] = await asyncio.gather(
        check_database(), check_redis()
    )
    all_ok = all(c["status"] == "ok" for c in checks.values())
    if not all_ok:
        response.status_code = 503
    return {
        "status": "ok" if all_ok else "degraded",
        "uptime_seconds": round(time.time() - START_TIME),
        "checks": checks,
    }

@app.get("/health/live")
async def health_live():
    return Response(status_code=200)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="systemd-watchdog-notify">
      <example type="good" title="Python systemd watchdog notification">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import os, socket, asyncio

def notify_watchdog():
    sock_path = os.environ.get("NOTIFY_SOCKET")
    if not sock_path:
        return
    sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_UNIX, socket.SOCK_DGRAM)
    try:
        sock.connect(sock_path)
        sock.send(b"WATCHDOG=1")
    finally:
        sock.close()

async def watchdog_loop():
    while True:
        notify_watchdog()
        await asyncio.sleep(15)  # WatchdogSec=30 / 2

@app.on_event("startup")
async def start_watchdog():
    asyncio.create_task(watchdog_loop())
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="auto-heal-service-check-class">
      <example type="good" title="Auto-heal ServiceCheck class with cooldown">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import time, subprocess, logging, urllib.request, json

CHECK_INTERVAL  = 60
MAX_RESTARTS    = 3
RESTART_COOLDOWN = 300  # 5 min

class ServiceCheck:
    def __init__(self, name, check_fn, restart_cmd):
        self.name = name
        self.check_fn = check_fn
        self.restart_cmd = restart_cmd
        self.restart_count = 0
        self.last_restart = 0

    def is_healthy(self):
        try:
            return self.check_fn()
        except Exception as e:
            logging.warning(f"{self.name}: health check error: {e}")
            return False

    def restart(self):
        now = time.time()
        if now - self.last_restart < RESTART_COOLDOWN:
            logging.warning(f"{self.name}: cooldown active, skipping restart")
            return
        if self.restart_count >= MAX_RESTARTS:
            logging.error(f"{self.name}: max restarts reached, manual intervention needed")
            return
        logging.info(f"Restarting {self.name}...")
        subprocess.run(self.restart_cmd, shell=True, check=True)
        self.restart_count += 1
        self.last_restart = now

def check_http(url):
    def _check():
        resp = urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=5)
        return json.loads(resp.read()).get("status") in ("ok", "degraded")
    return _check

def check_systemd(service):
    def _check():
        r = subprocess.run(["systemctl", "--user", "is-active", service],
                           capture_output=True, text=True)
        return r.stdout.strip() == "active"
    return _check
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="nero-platform-watcher-config">
      <example type="good" title="NERO platform watcher configuration">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
SERVICES = [
    ServiceCheck(
        "nero-core",
        check_celery("/srv/nero/nero-core/.venv", "nero_core"),
        "systemctl --user restart nero-core",
    ),
    ServiceCheck(
        "nero-channel-web",
        check_http("http://127.0.0.1:8100/health"),
        "systemctl --user restart nero-channel-web",
    ),
    ServiceCheck(
        "nero-channel-tg",
        check_systemd("nero-channel-tg"),
        "systemctl --user restart nero-channel-tg",
    ),
]
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="celery-health-check">
      <example type="good" title="Celery worker health check via inspect">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def check_celery(venv_path, app_name):
    def _check():
        result = subprocess.run(
            [f"{venv_path}/bin/celery", "-A", app_name, "inspect", "ping"],
            capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=10,
        )
        return "pong" in result.stdout.lower()
    return _check
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="rabbitmq-management-api-check">
      <example type="good" title="RabbitMQ node health and queue depth">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Node health
curl -su guest:guest http://localhost:15672/api/healthchecks/node

# Queue depth (alert if > 100 messages backed up)
depth=$(curl -su guest:guest http://localhost:15672/api/queues/%2F/celery | jq '.messages')
[ "$depth" -gt 100 ] && echo "WARNING: celery queue depth $depth"
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="telegram-alert-integration">
      <example type="good" title="Telegram alert helper script">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# alert.sh — Send alert via Telegram bot
MESSAGE="$1"
HOSTNAME=$(hostname)
TIMESTAMP=$(date -u +'%Y-%m-%d %H:%M UTC')

curl -s -X POST \
    "https://api.telegram.org/bot${TELEGRAM_ALERT_BOT_TOKEN}/sendMessage" \
    -d "chat_id=${TELEGRAM_ALERT_CHAT_ID}" \
    -d "text=[${HOSTNAME}] ${TIMESTAMP}%0A${MESSAGE}" >/dev/null
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

